::Applying Frameworks::A manager needs to announce a policy change requiring all employees to return to office 3 days per week. Using the know-feel-do framework, what would be an appropriate "FEEL" goal?{
~Employees should feel angry about losing flexibility #Unproductive - anger doesn't lead to compliance or smooth transition
~Employees should feel uncertain about the future #Uncertainty undermines trust and increases resistance
=Employees should feel reassured about the rationale and supported in the transition #Strategic FEEL goals should support message purpose and organizational goals. For a potentially unpopular policy change, the goal is not to make employees happy about losing flexibility, but to have them feel reassured about the reasoning and supported during transition. This aligns with credibility (care) and reduces resistance to change.
~Employees should feel confused about the policy details #Confusion suggests poor communication, not strategic outcome
}

::Cultural Considerations::Why did the lecture emphasize Vietnamese business communication context as "high-context"?{
=Vietnamese communication relies heavily on implicit messages and relationship context #Slide 18 (Vietnamese context example) explains that Vietnamese business culture is "high-context" - meaning communication relies heavily on implicit messages, relationships, and shared cultural understanding rather than explicit, direct statements. This contrasts with "low-context" Western business culture that values direct, explicit communication.
~Vietnamese businesses communicate only in formal settings #High-context doesn't mean formal only - it means relying on implicit understanding and context
~Vietnamese workplaces avoid written communication #Vietnamese businesses use extensive written communication
~Vietnamese professionals prefer long, detailed messages #Opposite - high-context cultures often prefer indirect, concise communication; low-context cultures prefer explicit detail
}
